<section class="card" id="gates">
<h2><span class="num">8</span>Hard Gates — last line of defense before fire</h2>

<p>The winning proposal still has to pass <code>PassesGlobalHardGates</code>. If it fails,
the ranker tries the second-place proposal once. If both fail → no trade.</p>

<table>
  <tr><th>Gate</th><th>What it checks</th><th>Setup exemptions</th></tr>
  <tr><td><code>InpEntryMaxSpreadPts</code></td><td>Spread ≤ 40 pts default</td><td>None</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>InpBlockEntryOnSpreadSpike</code></td><td>Block if spread &gt; 1.25× rolling p90</td><td>None</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Daily loss</td><td><code>g_DailyPnL ≤ -InpMaxDailyLoss</code></td><td>None</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Cooldowns</td><td>After loss / after any close</td><td>None</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Session</td><td><code>g_SessionOK</code></td><td>None</td></tr>
  <tr><td>News window</td><td><code>BlockNewEntriesDueToHighImpactNews</code></td><td><span class="chip red">News-Cont</span></td></tr>
  <tr><td>RSI caps</td><td><code>InpRsiBlockLongAbove</code> / <code>InpRsiBlockShortBelow</code></td><td><span class="chip ppl">Fade</span></td></tr>
  <tr><td>M15 vs trade</td><td>Block long if M15 bearish (and reverse)</td><td><span class="chip red">Spike</span> <span class="chip red">News</span> <span class="chip ppl">Fade</span></td></tr>
  <tr><td>H1 vs trade</td><td>Same for H1 (off by default)</td><td><span class="chip red">Spike</span> <span class="chip red">News</span> <span class="chip ppl">Fade</span></td></tr>
  <tr><td>M1 align filter</td><td>Last 3 M1 all in opposite color blocks</td><td><span class="chip red">Spike</span> <span class="chip red">News</span> <span class="chip ppl">Fade</span></td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>InpMinRRToFirstTarget</code></td><td>R:R ≥ 1.10 to T1</td><td>None</td></tr>
  <tr><td>$-risk cap</td><td>≤ <code>InpMaxRiskDollars</code> (or capped target ratio)</td><td>None</td></tr>
</table>

<div class="callout">
  <strong>Why exemptions exist</strong>
  Spike, News, and Fade catch <em>turns</em>. By definition the M15 / M1 trend at the moment they
  fire is often <em>opposite</em> to what's about to happen. Forcing HTF-alignment on those
  setups would defeat their entire purpose.
</div>
</section>

